BT 34.016 616.259 Td 1.671 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(A few thousand years ago people of the Fertile Crescent invented the technology of capturing words on flat )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 602.003 Td 0.879 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(surfaces using abstract symbols : literacy. The technology of literacy when first invented, and for thousands of )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 587.747 Td 0.699 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(years afterwards, was expensive, tightly controlled, precious. Today it effortlessly, unobtrusively, surrounds us. )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 573.491 Td 2.756 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(Look around now : how many objects and surfaces do you see with words on them ? Computers in the )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 559.235 Td 1.024 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(workplace can be as effortless, and ubiquitous, as that. Long-term the PC and workstation will wither because )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 544.979 Td 0.460 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(computing access will be everywhere : in the walls, on wrists, and in "scrap computers" \(like scrap paper\) lying )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 530.723 Td 0.000 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(about to be grabbed as needed. This is called "ubiquitous computing", or "ubicomp".)] TJ ET
BT 34.016 504.467 Td 1.150 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(I first created the idea of ubiquitous computing from contemplation of the place of today's computer in actual )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 490.211 Td 0.761 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(activities of everyday life. In particular, anthropological studies of work life [Suchman 1985, Lave 1991] teach )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 475.955 Td 0.523 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(us that people primarily work in a world of shared situations and unexamined technological skills. However the )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 461.699 Td 0.239 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(computer today is isolated and isolating from the overall situation, and fails to get out of the way of the work. In )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 447.443 Td 0.616 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(other words, rather than being a tool through which we work, and so which disappears from our awareness, the )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 433.187 Td 0.236 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(computer too often remains the focus of attention. And this is true throughout the domain of personal computing )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 418.931 Td 0.367 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(as currently implemented and discussed for the future, whether one thinks of PC's, palmtops, or dynabooks. The )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 404.675 Td 3.382 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(characterization of the future computer as the "intimate computer" [Kay 1991], or "rather like a human )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 390.419 Td 0.000 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(assistant" [Tesler 1991] makes this inappropriate attention to the machine itself particularly apparent.)] TJ ET
BT 34.016 364.163 Td 3.287 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(Ubiquitous computing has as its goal the enhancing computer use by making many computers available )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 349.907 Td 0.248 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(throughout the physical environment, but making them effectively invisible to the user. A number of researchers )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 335.651 Td 1.774 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(around the world are now working in the ubiquitous computing framework. Their work impacts all areas of )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 321.395 Td 1.704 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(computer science, including hardware components \(e.g. chips\), network protocols, interaction substrates \(e.g. )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 307.139 Td 0.000 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(software for screens and pens\), applications, privacy, and computational methods.)] TJ ET
BT 34.016 280.883 Td 0.284 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(Ubiquitous computing is not virtual reality, it is not a Personal Digital Assistant \(PDA\) such as Apple's Newton, )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 266.627 Td 2.249 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(it is not a personal or intimate computer with agents doing your bidding. Unlike virtual reality, ubiquitous )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 252.371 Td 3.285 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(computing endeavers to integrate information displays into the everyday physical world. It considers the )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 238.115 Td 3.387 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(nuances of the real world to be wonderful, and aims only to augment them. Unlike PDA's, ubiquitious )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 223.859 Td 2.518 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(computing envisions a world of fully connected devices, with cheap wireless networks everywhere; unlike )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 209.603 Td 0.223 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(PDA's, it postulates that you need not carry anything with you, since information will be accessable everywhere. )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 195.347 Td 0.188 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(Unlike the intimate agent computer that responds to one's voice and is a personal friend and assistant, ubiquitous )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 181.091 Td 1.069 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(computing envisions computation primarily in the background where it may not even be noticed. Whereas the )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 166.835 Td 0.000 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(intimate computer does your bidding, the ubiquitous computer leaves you feeling as though you did it yourself.)] TJ ET
BT 34.016 140.579 Td 2.823 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(Work on ubiquitous computing is still at an early phase. Most work now is concentrating on the mobile )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 126.323 Td 0.428 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(infrastructure for wireless networking. Because ubiquitous computing envisions hundreds of wireless computers )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 112.067 Td 0.866 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(in every office, its need for wireless bandwidth is prodigious. For instance, I work in a not-very-large building )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 97.811 Td 0.776 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(with 300 other people. If each of us has 100 wireless devices in our offices, each demanding 256 kbits/sec, we )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 83.555 Td 1.589 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(are using 7.5 gigabits of aggregate bandwidth in a single building. This is difficult to achieve with currently )] TJ ET
BT 34.016 69.299 Td 0.000 Tw /F2 12.0 Tf  [(envisioned wireless technologies.)] TJ ET
